SIMPLE: underhand
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Underhand
<hw>Un"der*hand`</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧n"d⟦etil⟧r*h⟦acr⟧nd`)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Secret; clandestine; hence, mean; unfair;
fraudulent.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball, Cricket, etc.)</fld> <def>Done, as
pitching, with the hand lower than the shoulder, or, as bowling, with
the hand lower than the elbow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Underhand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Underhand
<hw>Un"der*hand`</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧n"d⟦etil⟧r*h⟦acr⟧nd`)</pr>,
<pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>By secret means; in a clandestine
manner; hence, by fraud; unfairly; dishonorably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such mean revenge, committed <qex>underhand</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Baillie Macwheeble provided Janet, <qex>underhand</qex>, with meal
for their maintenance.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>In modern usage, the sense is usually negative.</note> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball, Cricket, etc.)</fld> <def>In an underhand
manner; thrown with the hand no higher than the shoulder and the palm
turned upward during part of the pitch; -- said of pitching or bowling a
ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Underhanded</ent>⟦br⟧
